inn1.comm: outside off stump, far too far outside off stump. Not the most convincing start
much straighter, and that leaps off a good length, into Cook's startled gloves. Lively
dabbed into the off side, and England are already fishing for run outs! Good grief that would have been close. As it is, the shy missed, and England are off the mark
cutting in from a good line, raps the thigh pad. This wicket has movement
zipping across the left-hander's bows, and left alone
a good leave in the end. Outside off, and nibbling off the seam
driven uncertainly through the leg-side, a bit of an inside-edge on that one. But runs all the same
outside off, nipping off the seam, through to the keeper
tucked down to backward point
short, and smeared square - past the out-stretched fingertips off Ryder at square leg - and all the way. Good, solid strike
fuller and straighter, and driven into the covers
outswinger, starting wide of off stump and curling past a flashing drive
zipping off the pitch again, through to the keeper. And that's the second over gone
through to the keeper
good carry outside off stump, Taken at chest height by the keeper
outside off, pushed into the covers with a checked defensive drive
loose drive, close to the off stump and sneaking past the inside edge
turned off the toes, picked up at midwicket
lovely delivery, and well left too. That past over the top of the off bail, more encouraging lift from a lively pitch. But New Zealand will want to make England play more frequently
Mustard played at that one alright, and played well. Riding the bounce to cut firmly through point. Not a lot of width to work with, but timed superbly
outside off stump, and left alone with a curtain-rail withdrawal of the bat
full and floaty, and too wide from Martin. And Mustard clobbered it through point with a sweet square drive
a good call - a rarety for England in this series - as Mustard tips and runs into the covers
zips off the pitch and defended into the covers with a late adjustment
big stride, and driven square into the hands of point
that was a violent swish, but nothing but thin air outside off stump
left alone outside off. Good carry again
on the pads and tucked very delicately behind square
better line this time, and through to the keeper
good stride once again, and driven firmly - but Vettori in the covers gets down quickly and fields exceptionally
a full half-volley, and that's Mustard's most attractive shot yet - down on one knee and drilled through the covers
slower ball, and steered to point with a swish of the wrists
dropped! - and that's an absolute clanger. Outside off, a regulation nick, and McCullum puts it down. It almost seemed as though he was celebrating before it arrived
outside off, and taken cleanly this time. Too late though ...
tighter to the stumps, and angling back in. Defended
a foot outside off and nipping off the seam
short, and pulled. It was a relief to have something to hit, but he didn't quite time it - snatched at it a fraction. No matter, it's three more to the total and a long chase for midwicket
driven, into the covers, but can't beat the field
flogged through the covers. That was momentarily intercepted by Taylor at short extra, but there was too much power on that shot.
nudged into space on the leg side. Good follow-up
short and angled across the left-hander. A mistimed cut to backward point
straighter, and angling into the left-hander's pads. Clipped square to keep the scoreboard ticking
driven into the covers again
short, but too short. Easily ducked
a wild slash outside off, extra bite off the seam allows the ball to sail through unhindered
tighter line, more encouraging bounce, through to the keeper
slashed drive, picked up in the covers
attempted yorker, well dug out
stands tall to drive, but picked up by the bowler
clipped off the pads, into space at midwicket
delicate late cut, well played but fielded at third man
straighter delivery, climbs into the middle of a defensive bat
shorter and pulled, not middled but well timed off an under-edge, and fine leg can't cut it off despite a big dive and slide
strides into a cover-drive, instant call and easily through for a single
fine delivery, angling in but shaping away, Cook prods uncertainly as it goes by
back and across, and dabbed to short midwicket for a quick single
slower ball, full length and drifting in towards off stump. Pushed to cover

bizarre passage of play. Mustard retreats to leg for a slog, Martin follows him, the ball ends up being smacked straight at the bowler's ankle, and ricochets away for a single. That's gotta hurt, but he's not winced yet ...
slower ball, defended
rippa. Climb, bounce and carry. Just beats the edge and through to the keeper
bouncer, but a slow one. Mustard is unaccustomed to the new pace, and almost swings himself off his feet
straighter, and defended with an uppish prod into the covers
steps across and into line for a pull. Nicely timed out to deep midwicket, all along the ground
clubbed straight through the line and no-one's going to cut that off. Another slower delivery, instantly picked, and that's the fifty partnership
pushed out to point
speared into the pads, defended off the back foot, and a quick call completes the over
short, and misdirected. McCullum takes well down the leg-side. Though I bet he's still ruing his one aberration ...
another delivery in a good channel, and in a Test match that might conceivably have been a regulation nick to fourth slip. Instead it races away fine
clobbered up and over the covers. Powerful swing through the line. Effective stuff
the pressure begins to tell as another one slides down leg ... Mustard's not letting them settle at present
turned off the hip, and excellent calling - two runs inside the circle. That's a rarety
slower ball, through to the keeper. Well disguised
superb timing - fine leg was up in the circle, but Mustard turned his wrists and the ball rocketed away
turned to leg again, but this time straight to fine leg
straight and full, jabbed back to the bowler
pretty much the same place, pushed across the line to mid-on
slower but too wide, he leans back and cuts behind square past backward point, lovely shot and super placement
overpitched and confidently driven off the front foot between cover and extra cover, it's pulled up just short of the rope
pushed to mid-on who has been forced slightly deeper by the flow of runs and that allows the single
back and pushed into the covers ... a rare dot ball
pushed with the angle into the leg side
steered to backward point off the back foot, slightly jumpily so
worked to third man, angled and a call of two, but only ever the one. Kidology, no more ...
too short, he leans back and cuts square and third man's despairing dive as he hurtles to his left just misses by a finger's length
good response, back and beaten with no real foot movement
turned slightly edgily square on the leg side
swished sweetly off his legs, one of those effortless strokes that has you purring, timed and square leg only had to retrieve it not to chase it
jabbed from some way away from him, little foot movement again, into the off side
prodded into the leg side
rather jerkily pushed to leg
he walks to the off and the bowler follows him and keeps him cramped and he has to push the ball defensively back
driven to wide mid-on
down the leg, flicks the pad and McCullum dives and makes a half-hearted appeal
he shapes to cut, it is too close to him and he improvises and chips it over where slips would have been had there been any
dropped a few feet to leg and a scurried single ... good running and that's the kind of single that sinks morale of fielders
short and larruped through midwicket for a one bounce four ... onto it in a  shot and his form is flooding back
caught back in his crease, he jabs down late and keeps out a straight one
driven to mid-on, the fielder's back on the circle and another easy single
half driven across the line to mid-on
outside off, straightens and beats a half poke, McCullum takes and whips off the bails
swept from outside off to the man at deep midwicket ...there for that very shot
drops too short, cut hard to the sweeper
a horrible reverse sweep, he misses and Vettori roars an appeal for leg before ... Billy Bowden not interested ... Vettori mutters and scowls and they run a leg bye
flicked into the leg side
inside edge into a pad, a loud appeal, Cook sets off, retreats, backward point underarms into the stumps, the ball cannons off and allows the overthrow ...

swished off his pads, long leg and deep midwicket converge and slide to stop it and they run three. Replays as the third umpire looks at Jesse Ryder's dive ... did he hit the rope before he flicked back? No definitive replays possible so no boundary
pulled hard on the bounce to deep midwicket where there is no issue about Ryder's stop
cut to point
driven into the covers, not timed and it bobbles harmlessly to the fielder
thuds into the pads as he aims to run behind square on the leg side
jumpily pushed back to the bowler
fuller and flatter, flicked along the ground to deep midwicket
hammered off one knee to short midwicket and well stopped
short, pulled hard to deep midwicket ... he almost lifted himself  off his feet as he hit that
turned defensively into the leg side
heaved over the infield to cow corner where it is fielded on the second bounce by one of two men out there
back, waits and flicks to the busy Ryder at deep midwicket
wide and short, much too much so, Mustard pulls out of the shot and it's signalled as a wide
a much better bouncer, he squats under it and that's perfectly legal
steps back and forehand smashes the ball high over extra cover, it clears the rope by a yard and as there was no one out there, a safe option
steered down to third man
as textbook as Mustard's slash was improvisational ... stands tall and thumps that through extra cover, the man in the deep slides but can't get near it
forward defensive push ... a tame end to an expensive over. Thirteen off it
back and turned square on the leg side
pushed to short mid-on from outside off stump
Vettori pulls down on it, short and pushed to deep midwicket, all along the ground
well controlled sweep from outside off
a big step forward and blocked
a grunt of exasperation from behind the stumps as Cook plays a late flick into the leg side
65mph to start, full on off stump, defended to extra cover
cut hard off the front foot to point
short, he steps back to cut but the shot is not timed
pulled, a shout of "catch it" but it is fielded by deep midwicket on the bounce
steered to third man
steps back and cuts hard to the sweeper
worked to short mid-on
wide and full, Cook lofts him over wide mid-on for a one-bounce four
tight response, defended to short mid-on with the spin
quicker ball, slightly hurried defensive push from the crease
worked past midwicket to the man out in the wastelands of deep midwicket
reverse swept on the half volley, almost sneaked under the bat but almost is not enough, it just has the legs to beat a sliding dive from the sweeper
cut into the ground and from there to point
hit over midwicket, Ryder, who is working up quite a sweat at deep midwicket, fields well
68.7mph, angled to deep backward point and some slack fielding allowed thoughts of a second ...but the throw was good
sweeps, misses, to short third man off the front-foot pad
driven uppishly a yard short of extra cover
slow enough for him to wait and thump to the sweeper
wide, slog-swept to wide midwicket
skips down the pitch and hit high over wide long-on, into a sponsor's marquee and that rattled a few tables
pushed to leg but at a fielder
fired flat down the leg side, McCullum half stops but cannot prevent the wide
a yard outside off, swept to deep midwicket who saves with a good sliding stop
back, soft hands takes all the pace off the ball and allows a single to extra cover
driven hard on the half volley to long-on
driven to Vettori at mid-off, the underarm throw hits the stumps but the batsman is home by a country mile
angled to point at 66mph, a fumble makes a tight single easy
defensive push to extra cover who is a few yards shorter than usual
back and pushed off middle stump to point
premeditated dab-sweep, edged uppishly but safe
driven with a very late opening of the face to point
wide and full, driven to long-off
yorker but wide, good take from McCullum at his feet and he whips the bails off for good measure
steps to leg, and he almost gets yorked but a thin edge saves him... the balls squirts to leg
low full toss, thumped at midwicket who stops smartly
driven to Oram ten yards in from the long-on boundary, the fielder never had to move
two in two as Cook plays all round a straight one and has his middle stump pegged back ... a jubilant Ryder is mobbed as well he might be as he's removed both openers in his first over
outside off, slightly short, left
a big stride down the pitch and steered to point
outside off, Bell not tempted
back and punched off the back foot to cover, misfielded but no run
mid-on fields
short and wide, Bell follows with a loose drive which misses but provokes some oohs from the crowd
full and driven to mid-on
up in the blockhole - metrognomic with his length so far - blocked
flicked to midwicket who is halfway back
clipped off his legs and midwicket dives and gathers as it is almost past him
checked drive to mid-on
driven softly to mid-on
slashed drive from outside off stump scoots high over the slips, third man makes a good diving stop
slower - 71mph - but too wide and full, Bell waits and caresses the ball between cover and extra cover
late in pulling the bat out of the way, the ball hits it and dribbles into the slips
another rasping drive through the covers, too full and too wide, and with the third Powerplay being taken there is nobody out there
a peach, back of a length at 85mph, cuts off the pitch away from Bell, enough to beat the outside edge
another one Bell is able to driven, it beats the infield but Vettori has had to reinforce the deep and the sweeper round to cut it off
misdirected full toss - Pietersen was dancing at the crease and created that opportunity. Sweetly timed off the pads through midwicket
clipped wide of short midwicket for a jogged single
tucked off the toes again, Chris Martin dives valiantly at fine leg and just intercepts the boundary
another low full toss, but driven straight to cover
a classic whip of the wrists from Pietersen - dunno how he does that without snapping his hands. But he does
driven into the covers. Good milkage in that over
wicket to wicket. Defended on the back foot in front of middle
defended again. Stoically straight bat
tucked off the pads again, wide of square leg
a step down the track, but defended on off stump once again
nurdled off a good line and length, through midwicket. Tight over so far. No freebies and little pace to work with
tucked behind square again
good line, good length, defended
tucked to the leg side again
strange flick around the corner - in position for the pull, but in the end opted for a paddle
nudged into space behind square
excellent restrictive spell now. The hardness has gone, and with it the bounce. Just tight line and length
another single to mid-on, and another over in the can
turned to short midwicket with a loud "no!"
drawn onto the front foot, and defended again
a slap into the deep - it looked like it was disappearing for six, but in the end plugged just in front of the despairing long-off as he ran in. Lucky
worked into the covers
Pietersen takes the slapper's option, so to speak, this time. And again it lands short. A mite chancey
forward, and defended
big stride forward, and defended to midwicket
tucked off the hip to fine leg
slower delivery, Bell comes forward to drive but is beaten
turned off the toes, picked up in the deep
played into the covers
push and run, picked up at mid-off, but the batsman is home
spun towards the pads, and tucked to leg
defended with an angled bat, off middle and leg, and that's the 200 up
a shimmy down the wicket and a lovely lofted drive. Well struck and no stopping that
thought about two to wide mid-on, but Pietersen declines
energetic use of the feet from Pietersen - momentarily defeated in the flight. But recovered well enough with a nudge to midwicket
pushed into the covers to end the over
down on one knee and a mighty pre-meditated swipe across the line. Slog-swept to perfection
pushed down the pitch to long-on
stands tall and defends from the crease to be picked up in the covers
turned on the pads - in the air for a while, but always safe. Long-on fields
incredible. Hard to explain quite how that sailed flat and fast over deep midwicket, when he was cramped for room and defeated on length. But it flew alright
toe-ended out to the deep, but lands safe. That was lucky. The bowler saw him coming and deliberately threw it out wide
swept firmly once again, but the sweeper tidies up
faster, flatter, and hurried. Yelps of dismay as that's defended on middle
top strike, waited and waited, and cracked behind point. Nothing wrong with the ball at all, but superb batting
defended out to point
nurdled out to midwicket
off-stump line, pushed down the ground, easy single
defended solidly into the covers
short and mown over midwicket - Bell picked that length so quickly and the fielder never had a chance
short again, but not quite as short. Bell rides the bounce and drives into the covers
steps across the stumps, and whipped straight to midwicket. Nice timing, but the placement was awry
picks the gap this time, worked from way outside off stump, and the sweeper picks up on the midwicket boundary

the breakthrough at last, and O'Brien has his maiden scalp. Short, but a touch quicker than England have been used to in recent overs. A steepling top-edge, well pouched in the deep by Kyle Mills. Timely for New Zealand, but a handy innings nonetheless
On off stump, defended
short, effortlessly swatted high into the stand over deep midwicket, about 20 rows back
pushed to midwicket, swiveling as he plays it
straight drive with no follow through, long-on trots in to field
pushed, almost fenced, to point
slowish ball - 69mph - nurdled to midwicket
hard drive back at the feet of the bowler, he drops a hand and takes some of the pace off it
loose drive, feeling for it with little footwork, McCullum takes and then throws at and hits the stumps. Collingwood had gone nowhere
turned square and surprised by some extra bounce, the ball takes a a thick edge and lobs safely well short of point
full toss driven up to long-on
ball hits back rather than the other way round, deliberately, the pace comes off the ball and they scamper a single to point
driven to extra cover, slightly open face and two yards short of the man
worked from outside off to wide midwicket, he was ambling towards the covers as the bowler was in his delivery stride
one stride and flicked off his toes high over square leg, a dozen rows back. A triumph of timing
even bigger ... a step to the off and hit higher and harder, it strikes the roof and clumps down into spectators underneath. O'Brien shakes his head ...
short and pacy, Collingwood again steps to the off and he plays a slightly rushed but controlled pull to the man at deep midwicket lurking in the shadows
O'Brien's inexperience shows ... he again bangs one in and Pietersen is there and waiting, pulling hard and square, deep midwicket has no chance
short and slow outside off, forehand swat to deepish extra cover
full and all he could do was drive it up to long-on
low full toss driven to Fulton at wide long-on, a good throw but a comfortable two as the fielder has a lot of ground to cover
pushed to square leg, he started as if to hit it high but checked when cramped for room
skips to leg and drives on the full to long-on, super running from Collingwood who was back for the second to the danger end like a whippet
he tries to follow the batsman but he had not moved to leg and the ball arcs very wide to McCullum
flicked off his feet to deep midwicket
fitty for KP with a dead-batted poke to midwicket
slightly short, he rocks back and lofts that over midwicket and only five or six rows back that time ... flatter and harder
cracked hard to extra cover
squeezed to backward point, a wild throw from the hapless O'Brien gives an overthrow as even a full-length dive from McCullum cannot get near it
cunning stuff ... Vettori holds one back, Pietersen is way too early as he aims to thump the ball over midwicket and the ball ever-so-gently clomps into the stumps
flicked to square leg, short fine leg round to field
pushed from the crease to point
thumped hard to the left of Oram but only the one as long-off and long-on are in the deep
dropped ... no more than pushed, albeit firmly, back at Oram who picks it up take and never looks like catching a head-high chance
punched into the pitch a yard to the off from the back foot, all pace off the ball and an easy one
Oram follows the batsman and cramps him enough so he can only manage the one
lovely yorker as Shah shimmied to the off, he has to adjust and jab down on it, falling to the off as he does so
slower but, unlike KP, he's not fooled, down on one knee and it's launched over the leg-side boundary
firm drive through extra cover
firm drive with his trademark follow through, the sweeper round to field

another wicket for Vettori but they are coming at a cost ... tossed up, Shah goes for the straight six but gets too much elevation and Fulton has time to come five yards in from the boundary to take a good catch at long-off
pushed hard to wide long-on
edgily turned to short fine leg, Collingwood yells "no" as he starts as if looking for a sharp single
two strides and an ugly head-in-the-air heave to one outside off misses by some way
yorker dug into the covers between the two men inside the circle
slow half volley thumped down the ground ... "that's out" calls our BBB man ... and sure enough it carries ten yards over long-on
full toss hammered to deep midwicket
wide half volley, the batsman had moved to leg and had to reach to squirt the ball through the covers
full toss heaved to wide long-on, not timed but still he is able to come back for an easy second as it was between men out in the deep
utterly daft bowling ... Collingwood moves to the off and Martin serves him an inviting short one which he thumps over square leg
outside off and full, leans back and hits hard to long-on
driven square off one knee, hard to Ross Taylor who is out sweeping

a step the off and swatted over square leg, into the stands again and he has a fifty off 24 balls. it includes six sixes all over midwicket/square leg ... but no fours!  And what's more it's the fastest one-day fifty by an England player ...
driven to extra cover
he gives himself room and squirts the ball square on the off side, it goes like a bullet
slow wide full toss, punched to long-off
slightly reaches for a drive, extra cover fields
long-off once more into action
high full toss, Wright seemed to do anything but middle it but it still raced for a one-bounce four past straight long-on
back and pulled hard to deep midwicket
good last ball, in at his feet, Collingwood works to leg for a single
yorker outside off, he shapes to swing over midwicket, it clips his boot and McCullum fields well
Collingwood's intentions are clear as he again takes a big and early step to the off, Martin counters with a yorker aimed at him rather than the stumps, it hits him on the pads and dribbles to point
oh dear ... Wright looks to paddle the ball over the keeper, misses, it bounces in front of McCullum who, tiredly, lets it through his legs
low fulls toss hit off the bottom of the bat, long-on fields but he should have not allowed them to come back for such an easy second
a step and driven hard to long-off while on one knee, again Collingwood hurtles back to the danger end to get a second

low full toss hit high towards long-on, Fulton sprints in, makes a lot of ground, dives, and holds the ball a foot above the turf. An excellent catch for the big man gets the crowd excited but it's all rather late ...

inn2.comm: short and slightly leg-sided, an attempted flick falls short of Ryan Sidebottom at short fine leg
short again, and defended on the back foot
short again, and Ryder doesn't miss out three times in a row. Flipped up and over short fine leg, and that's a gifted four runs
short again, that's pretty ordinary bowling, and Sidebottom at fine leg so nearly scoops up a bonus catch. This isn't the right line at all
short, leg side again, flicked airily into the vacant square leg region. Not very impressive in this over so far
short and wide outside off, McCullum slashes loosely and third man gathers
Sidebottom gets it right straightaway, full and swinging into the right hander, tucked to square leg
outside off and swinging away. Left alone
defended off the back foot
driven on the back foot, fielded in Sidebottom's followthrough
tucked off the pads, fielded at midwicket
shaping from leg to off, met with a full face and worked through midwicket
no, he hasn't. Wild down the leg side, to the right hander this time
attempted inswinger, chopped down to third man
short, but not as short as the rest of them. Swung high and handsome over wide long-on, and fielded inside the rope by Broad
McCullum tries to cut, but finds thin air. Still too short though ...
short again, but at least there's a bit of venom about that one - McCullum got out to a similar shot at Auckland. Perhaps that explains his current length?
short again, and McCullum is swinging wildly. Any contact and that would have flown
that's the spot - fuller and angling in, McCullum is anchored on the back foot, and gets forward late and very tentatively. Better finish to the over
driven off the back foot to cover
defended into the crease, thoughts about a quick single, but wisely reconsidered
good length, defended into the covers
swish and a miss. Outside off stump and fizzing through to Mustard
a firm push off the back foot, can't beat the field as Bell slides round at cover. But one more to the total
a bit unlucky to be called for that one - McCullum hopped across his crease so Sidebottom was within his rights to target leg stump
that'll annoy Sidebottom even more. A streaky drive, a thick inside-edge and four through an unguarded fine leg
short, and wellied into the leg-side, agonisingly close to a diving Broad at wide mid-on. Not timed at all, but that's runs all the same
dropped - though it's harsh to call it a chance. A strangle down the leg-side, just eluding the diving Mustard. Still, a chance is a chance ...
short again, and that's sweetly uppercut over backward point. Wrong line ...
better line, and McCullum's in trouble. Cramped for room by a short ball and rapped flush on the right hand as he withdrew the bat. The physio is out ...
far too much width, and Ryder clobbers that on one knee through point
misses out, to complete the statto's Grand Slam. This over has contained a dot ball, a one, a two, a three, a four and a six. Count them for yourself. It's fascinating
the best ball of the innings, pitching on off, cutting back in, and just missing everything
pre-meditated step across the crease. No contact. He's looking jittery
defended down to third man with an open face. He's off the strike for now, which is probably the best place to be for a bit
driven square, not great power but wonderful timing. Collingwood half-stops at point
outside off, seaming back in and climbing at the gloves. Left alone
tip and run, picked up in the covers
nudged into the leg side
stand and deliver! That is massive. Just a dismissive swipe through the line - Anderson gave him room to free his arms, that was a good length too. Food for thought
good ball, on a length, on off stump, and pumped through the covers with outstanding timing
slower ball, full length, not timed
sweetly driven again, but short extra cover intercepts
smeared down the ground again, too full and wide, and walloped. England have to make a change, because Anderson is going round the park
a hop across the crease - McCullum is looking merely to rotate the strike at the mo, and why wouldn't he?
outside off and seaming away. A little prod as the ball goes past, more in hope than expectation
on the back foot, pushed into the covers. Can't escape the strike yet
cracking delivery, explodes off the seam and into Mustard's upturned gloves
finds the gap at last, but it's only one ball left for Ryder
tucked off the hip and that's well played. Finds the single New Zealand wanted, and Ryder has the strike again
another elegant drive, leaning onto the front foot and timed to perfection. But straight to cover on this occasion
short, and whisked round the corner for a single
outside off stump, hopping across the stumps to defend into the leg side. Still looking to hand the strike back, rather than make the big shots himself
wristy steer into the covers, and there's the single
dabbed down to third man, another single
gives himself masses of room, almost too much room, and no contact as a short ball zings through
down the leg-side, a strangled appeal as the ball brushes thigh-pad
straying down leg, whipped to backward square
pre-meditated, and Sidebottom ended up too short, swung away behind square with excellent timing. That'll make him field better
full toss outside off, and busted finger or not, that's a gimme. Opens the face and runs through the covers with nothing more than timing
better line and length, defended into the leg side
outside off, and defended out to point

a wider and slower ball, swung high from outside off stump, it climbs miles into the sky, three men converge at deepish straight midwicket and it's Anderson who holds a superb catch running flat out to his left
flicked into the leg side
outside off stump, through to the keeper as he fends very half heartedly
good line from Broad, nothing there to hit
pushed square into the off side, a momentary uncertainty between the batsmen but the fielders have a renewed spring in their step after the wicket
checked drive half stopped by Broad, and that's enough
shuffles to the off and pushes to mid-off
slanted across him and he shoulders arms
tight line, on off stump, How solidly defends
turned with all wrists to midwicket
it passes over leg stump as he moves to the off and aims to flick into the on side
quicker ball through the batsman before he plays at it
stands tall and pushes to extra cover
thick edge and he pushes hard at the ball, Sidebottom scurries round at third man to cut it off
whoa, outside off and it takes off, snorting past McCullum and Mustard takes a above his head
daftness ... even shorter and it zips over McCullum and even a leaping Mustard has no chance
not quite as short but wide outside off - swinging wider - and again it's called
back on some kind of line and length, a single into the off side
much better, on off stump, upright drive to mid-off
back of a length and into McCullum off the seam, he can do no more than defend off the back foot
slightly short, he jumps to get over it and drops it into the leg side
short and How onto it in a flash, pulls with real venom off the front foot and it hums through midwicket
driven hard into the ground, it arcs over Anderson but mid-off round very quickly to mop up
steps to leg, Anderson follows and fires one in at his feet
yorker and a quick one as well, he does well to jam down on it
a good over from Anderson after a poor start to his second spell. But it's all relative ...
no more than a firm push but timed and placed, it beats a full-length dive from extra cover and carries on its way
good length on off stump, defended
turned off his hips to Sidebottom at square leg, again with a leap
now that's a lovely shot, full and driven from the crease, his feet were planted but it was all about timing and extra cover had no chance
yorker, dug out into the off side
cross-batted swipe to mid-on. As ugly as the previous four was delightful
speared in at his feet but slightly off, a good take by Mustard but it's a wide
that's what he was aiming for, straighter but still yorker-length
low full toss as he goes for another yorker, driven down the ground
overpitched, swung to square leg, all along the ground
he strays to leg and this time the leg-side flick beats the man in the deep
full toss steered to the left of midwicket
short, McCullum quick to duck
punched into the pitch on the off side and a good run, out of the blocks so fast even though the ball hardly went more than a pitch width away
back and turned between midwicket and mid-on
two steps down the track and pulled hard past midwicket ... another four
square drive off the front foot, the sweeper fields
slightly short and he is forced onto the back foot, dropped a few yards into the off side and Broad quickly adjusts to field
too short for Rauf's liking and he is quite right
inswinging yorker - 81mph - pushed to mid-on
swinging away rather gently, driven to cover
steps to leg but does no more than pat into the off side - 64mph ...
fuller, turned off his toes to deep square leg
back, waits, and flicks square on the leg side for an ambled single
low full toss driven to long-on
back and then a big stride forward to defend
pulled off the front foot through midwicket
one step and a good old-fashioned across-the-line slog ... he misses by a good way and Mustard takes low down
very firm drive through the covers but there's a sweeper back in the shade of the stand
pushed into the covers off the back foot to bring up his 11th one-day fifty
worked to the left of midwicket
a yorker at 82mph which he turns into a low full toss by using his feet, driven to wide long-off
straight and defended gently back to the bowler
very correct forward defensive prod
steps back but is followed by an offcutter and he can do no more than push to point
defended with an open-faced dead bat
blocked but it beats Collingwood and they take a sharp single as mid-off is on the edge of the circle
steps to leg, aims an expansive drive, misses and Mustard takes one well at his feet
pushed from the crease to cover and they take a quick single
pushed to mid-on who is two-thirds back
patted to cover, Collingwood is quick to gather and throw but he is back on the edge of the circle and he can't prevent the run
inside edge to short mid-on
he waits and flicks to midwicket
angled behind square on the off side
back and pushed to cover
drifts to leg, they think about two but Sidebottom in quick enough to prevent it
pulled from outside off but not middled and the ball bobbles to the man in the deep
back, jumps and pushes to cover, both men on the same wavelength and that means the run is easily made
he shimmies to leg, Collingwood follows, and all How can do is drive back to the bowler
a lot of effort - driven to deep cover -  for little reward
punched through the cover ring
driven hard but into the pitch, the ball scuttles to long-on
risk-free drive up and over mid-off who is on the edge of the circle, hit on the up
slower delivery, good running as Anderson at long-off had a lot of ground to make up
Anderson has gone wider and so only the one to the same area
back but turned square, a thick edge zips to backward point
hard straight drive, well stopped by the bowler
Collingwood drifts onto leg stump and How quick to sweep high into the crowd over backward square leg
short, pulled flatter and harder and squarer ... but the same result
better line and length, fuller and driven to short mid-on
flicked to Wright at deep wide midwicket
quicker - 78mph - defended to short midwicket
beats him as he tries to turn to leg, a loud shout but it hit him outside the line
very wide, beats a prod and is eventually called a wide, but very late on
driven to long-on

beaten outside the off stump, Mustard whips off the bails and McCullum turns and starts to head off before the umpire beckons him to stay and wait for the third umpire. It's a short reprieve ... he dragged a long way out and while his foot was back it wasn't grounded
wide of off stump, he reaches and pushes hard through the covers
tossed up -53mph - patted back to Shah
swept all along the ground to deep square leg
steered behind square on the off and well stopped by a diving Collingwood
wristily flicked off his legs
good line from over the wicket, Taylor pushes to short midwicket
angled across the right hander, it holds its line and beats the outside edge of a defensive jab
fuller and on off stump, defended and Sidebottom sharply down to field
half forward, jabbed to cover
a lot of width, full, driven through the covers
opens the face and square drives a yorker-length ball outside off
chipped over short midwicket
completely miscued off the inside edge and again it's too close to short midwicket for thew batsman's comfort
much flatter, Shah fields off his own bowling
up in the blockhole, he opens the face and runs it into the off side
Sidebottom allowed to settle into a groove, slightly short and angled into the batsman who has to defend from the crease
half volley outside off driven to the sweeper
thick inside edge to square leg, Anderson at midwicket round to field
turned firmly off leg stump
pulled-driven off the front foot hard past a diving Anderson at midwicket. The pace did for the fielder as it was within his reach but really thumped
angled across the batsman who feels for it and misses
outside off, close to a wide, no shot offered
too wide and it got wider, an easy call for Bowden
swished to leg and a tight two made easier by a poor pick-up from Cook
defended, he looks for a single but it's never on as extra cover was in quickly
flatter and on off stump, defended back to the bowler
dead on 60mph, pushed into a gap in the covers
outside off, Shah again fields a defensive push
outside off and enough width for Taylor to cut that with venom behind square
straighter and defended off the back foot
patted into the covers but it bounces kindly for the incoming fielder and that prevents the single
outside off and the batsman knows it will be called a wide and so lets it pass. Umpire Rauf obliges
sweep-pulled, onto it so quickly and hit with power into the stands
inswinging yorker that the batsman can do no more than dig out
wide full toss gets exactly what it deserves, slashed square and it rockets to the boundary
down on one knee, and swung down to midwicket
whisked into the leg side again
edged, towards the third-man boundary, but not got the legs to get there
better length, respectfully driven back down the pitch
in the air, and just wide of Sidebottom, flinging himself to his left at gully. That was too wide though, and the risk was calculated
worked into space to complete another eventful over. England are struggling to make an impact here
good length, pushed back up the pitch
worked off the pads, and picked up at square
driven through midwicket
whipped off the toes, and one bounce over the ropes. There was a man back for the stroke, but he never got close
drawn forward and defended
offcutter, slightly back of a length, dabbed down to third man
too short, but cut straight to backward point. A let-off
drifting down leg, and flicked away
good line and length, looped onto middle and driven down to long-on
pulled across the line and very nearly into the hands of midwicket. Too short again, although Broad does well on the boundary's edge
too wide this time, cut away without alarm
swept coolly to deep square. England desperately need a wicket now
thumped firmly down the ground to mid-on
drilled into the deep cover region, and still the haemorrageing of runs continues
floaty and full, an lbw-candidate of a ball, but not if it's middled that sweetly. Midwicket fields
pushed firmly back down the pitch, Collingwood leaps to field in his followthrough
tapped off the toes, and picked up in the deep
dabbed out to point
big stride, and pushed into the covers
cracking strike! Remarkably it whistles all the way over the ropes, even though it was nothing more than a checked drive
another run to deep midwicket
massive appeal for anything and everything. Shah hops around like a bunny on a gas-hob. Might have been lbw, a catch at the wicket. Good ball though
defended
down on one knee and swung through midwicket
too much width, and cut down to third man
tidy strike to deep cover
pops off a thick edge, a big cry goes up from the stumps, but that lands in no-man's land
big swing across the line, completely missed, and not a bad shout for lbw. A fraction high?
connection with the midwicket mow this time, but fielded under the stands
worked into space on the leg-side, and that's a new career-best for Jamie How
dabbed behind square, and that's wonderfully timed. Quick outfield, no stopping that. Nor New Zealand, at this rate
down the leg side
nudged into the deep, another single
low full toss, and clubbed down to long off
another single
a top-edge, but lands well short of Cook on the sweep
pushed down to long-on to complete
full, straight and defended. A good start
low full toss, and an inside edge flies through the batsman's legs and away through the unguarded fine leg
redemption for Anderson, and a vital life-line for England. Outside off, hard-handed swish, clear edge, simple catch. Well bowled, and a window of opportunity
full length, driven into the covers, and off the mark first-ball
leg-side full toss, whipped to deep square. He's targeting the yorker, but not quite nailing it
banged in short, not called as wide, an encouraging over for England
back, defensive push to deep mid-on
back of a length outside off, defended
they take on Collingwood haring in from point, his throw at the bowler's end misses and Styris would have just about made it anyhow
square drive, a tumbling stop from Collingwood
uppish drive, Bell at cover claws the ball back as it seemed past him
rasping cover drive, too full and stroked all along the ground past cover and the sweeper has no chance
poodled to long-on
firm drive placed to the left of mid-off
angled behind square on the off, How wants the second and he gets it as Broad's throw is wild ... he raises his left arm to punch the air as he makes his ground
"two, two" he shouts as he on drives wide of Sidebottom at long-on
inswinging yorker which is very late to jab down on, the fielders are slow and they still get a single ... heads are drooping out there with every run
he ends with a rare dot ball on off stump
hit firmly back at the bowler who is down quickly
driven straight inches to the right of the stumps, long-on fields
pulled from off stump to the long boundary, and into the breeze as well, Mustard screams "catch" but it's a big six
cut behind square, Anderson tumbles and picks up but can't prevent the run
tip and run into the off
short and pulled to deep midwicket
full toss on off stump, driven to mid-off
pushed into the covers
spanked square, a slower ball that ended up as a slow long hop and got exactly what it deserved
full and wide, squeezed to third man
wide full toss, slammed into the ground and Bell stops well as it was coming out of the setting sun
pushed into the off side ... all very easy
upright drive to long-off
he checks a drive and the ball loops back a yard or so short of the bowler
sweet paddle fine on the leg side, Shah dives but more for show as he was well beaten. "Cheeky but effective," says Sir Ian
short and pulled hard past midwicket, the man in the deep called into action
square drive to deep cover
up on the crease and wide, but he can still guide the ball wide of backward point
oh yes, full and straight, threaded between midwicket and mid-on, a lovely shot
a wry grin as he misses out ... a full toss hit hard but right at midwicket
driven uppishly but a few yards short of the inrushing long-off
he goes for the big hit over long-on, doesn't quite get hold of it and Anderson takes the catch two yards inside the rope
a swish and a miss, but a leg bye into the on side
How still firing, a placed cover drive keeps him on strike
pushed to leg, Mustard implores the fielders to make the extra effort
steered wide of backward point but Anderson makes an athletic tumbling stop
driven into the stumps at the bowler's end
chipped short of mid-on, Pietersen picks up on the half volley and underarms off balance as he is falling and hits the bowler's end stumps with Fulton a foot short
flicked wide of midwicket, Oram was coming back come hell or high water and he makes his ground easily
fired down the leg side. Mustard can't gather first time and he misses a stumping chance ... it was very wide but the batsman overbalanced and was some way adrift
too short and pulled hard to deep midwicket
inswinging and full, driven into the off side
pushed drive to the left of the stumps, nice shot, long-on fields
slightly short, he tries a rather ambitious flick through the slips and plays under the ball
clubbed with almost no backlift back Bell at backward point
wide, driven hard with no footwork but straight at Pietersen at extra cover who holds a sharp catch at thigh height
wide and full, squeezed through the covers
chops into the ground at his feet as he looks to guide the ball to third man
just what England wanted, full and slanted across Vettori who does well not to nick it
and another peach which again leaves Vettori who gropes and misses
finally Vettori middles one into  the covers and gets How on strike
inswinging full toss, hit hard back at Anderson who dives to his right and makes a good save
again full and swinging in, driven to long-off
full and outside off stump, guided with an open face to deepish cover
classic yorker, outside off swinging into the left hander and rips through him
half volley driven to long-on but with no power
wide full toss, hit with oodles of bottom hand to long-on
almost a yorker, Vettori does well to drive back to the right of a diving Sidebottom, long-off mops up
more bottom hand, turned to the right of long-on, Vettori turns for the second without looking at Anderson whose throw is accurate but the batsman makes his ground
clubbed over long-on
fuller and only a single to long-on this time
not timed, long-on fields one that was aimed into the off side

Vettori shimmies to the off and works behind square on the leg, Sidebottom does well to slide and throw at fine leg, Mustard fumbles the return ... had he not, it would have been mighty close ...but it's all academic
same shot, right across his stumps, steered right to Sidebottom this time but still the single
a good delivery to finish a poor day with the ball for Anderson, up in the blockhole and a single into the leg side
full, straight and hit to long-on
bottom edge into the ground, it scoots to Broad at short fine leg
driven very hard to long-on, yet again Vettori takes on the arm and this time he gets home without the third umpire being needed  ... not that he did England any favours last time!
hit hard to midwicket, Pietersen gathers cleanly and hurls at the bowler's end ... it misses by inches with the batsman nowhere to be seen
full toss hit hard to mid-off, Anderson picks up and throws down the bowler's end stumps with the batsman yards short

the ball is fired in at his feet, it cannons off his boot with some edge as well into the off side, the batsmen run, a diving underarm throw misses as Mills hurls himself towards the crease ... and he makes it. We have a tie!
